Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Peel and dice @sweet potatoes{2} into ½-inch pieces; transfer to a medium pot with enough
salted water to cover by 2 inches.

Bring to a boil and cook until tender, ~{15-20%minutes}. Reserve ½ cup sweet potato cooking
liquid, then drain and return sweet potatoes to pot. Keep covered off heat until ready
to mash.

While sweet potatoes cook, trim and finely chop @scallions{2}(greens only) (save whites for
another use). Trim @green beans{6%oz} if necessary.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @mayonnaise{2%tbsp}, @Dijon mustard{2%tsp}, half the
@garlic powder{1%tsp} (you'll use the rest in the next step), and @sugar{1/2%tsp}.
Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Transfer 2 TBSP sauce (4 TBSP for 4) to a separate
small bowl; reserve for serving.

Melt @butter{1%tbsp} (2 TBSP for 4 servings) in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat.
Add @panko breadcrumbs{1/4%cup} and toast, stirring, until golden and fragrant,
~{2-3%minutes}.

Turn off heat; transfer to a #shallow dish{} and stir in @Parmesan cheese{3%tbsp},
half the scallion greens, remaining garlic powder, and a pinch of salt and pepper.
Wipe out pan.

Pat @steelhead trout{10%oz} dry with #paper towels{}; season with salt and pepper. Drizzle
skin sides with @cooking oil{2%tsp}; rub to coat.

Place trout, skin sides down, on a #baking sheet{}. Evenly spread tops with 1 tsp sauce
each; mound with panko mixture, pressing firmly to adhere.

Roast on top rack until trout is cooked through and cheese melts, ~{10-12%minutes}.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of oil in pan used for panko over medium-high heat. Add green
beans; season with salt and pepper. Cook, stirring occasionally, until browned and
tender, ~{5-7%minutes}.

Remove from heat; stir in @sliced almonds{1/2%oz} and @butter{1%tbsp}. Continue to stir
until butter is melted and almonds are golden, ~{30-60%seconds}.

> TIP: Return pan to low heat if needed to melt butter.

Cover to keep warm.

While green beans cook, to bowl with reserved sauce, add water 1 tsp at a time until
mixture reaches a drizzling consistency.

To pot with sweet potatoes, add @sour cream{1.5%tbsp}, @butter{1%tbsp}, and a big
pinch of salt. Mash with a #potato masher{} until smooth, adding splashes of reserved
sweet potato cooking liquid as needed.

Stir in remaining scallion greens; taste and season with salt and pepper.

Divide trout, mashed sweet potatoes, and green beans between plates. Top trout with
reserved sauce and serve.

> Trout is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.